	(text "[mcu-control] Microcontroller and USB-C PD Interface"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 97.79 22.86 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 2.032 2.032)
				(thickness 0.4064)
				(bold yes)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
		)
		(uuid "1dc18e65-e458-4639-89fb-73ccc74a7229")
	)
	(text "* Two main LOGICAL buses are routed throughout the board:\n\n  - USER: The USER bus is focused on controlling the board itself (SoC/MCU), e.g. setting up\n    configuration, issuing commands, retrieving collected data, etc. It has a single physical\n    bus with at most two wires, and can be multi-protocol (one chosen at a time). It can be a\n    multi-master bus, when configured as I2C.\n\n    As a rule, in this bus, the board (SoC/MCU) acts as a SLAVE, but depending on the mode of\n    operation, the bus can be used as a secondary PHER bus, or it can be just converted to\n    simple GPIOs.\n\n  - PHER: The Pheripheral bus is where the devices the board controls directly are located;\n    e.g. the fuel gauge, battery charger, miscellaneous devices like screens or EEPROMs, etc.\n    For this bus, the board (SoC/MCU) acts strictly as a MASTER, but it can be configured\n    to be multi-master. It is I2C-only.\n\n* The board operates in two distinct and fixed modes, programmable at the firmware level:\n\n  - STANDALONE: The board is meant to run without supervision. It will be configured by default\n    in SoC/MCU firmware, or if enabled, interactively via a pre-specified \"HAT\" (if supported;\n    e.g. additional EEPROM storage, screen with touch or buttons, etc.). In this mode, the board\n    acts as MASTER in both USER and PHER buses.\n\n  - MANAGED: The board is meant to be controlled by a host system. The board acts as a MASTER\n    in the PHER bus, and as a SLAVE in the USER bus.\n\n* The physical buses for PHER/USER support specific bus types, selectable at firmware level:\n\n  - USER1: I2C or UART.\n  - PHER1: I2C.\n\n  External strong pull-ups are always present, and pull to 3.3V.\n  See Pinouts on the table below.\n\n* To the MCU all lines are 5V-tolerant except for pins PA4 and PA5. However, try to avoid\n  presenting 5V on any non-5V bus.\n\n* If the MCU is configured to sleep at Standby level, it will only wake up on ~{PHER1_IRQ1}\n  or ~{USER_IRQB} assertion (low-level, on falling edge). The pins PA0 and PA2 are configured\n  as system wake-up pins at firmware level.\n\n* The ~{BTN} is the general purpose User Button. It can be used by the host for any purpose.\n  The MCU can be configured to capture when it's pressed and perform operations (e.g. notify\n  the host, change PDOs, etc. Because it's connected to BQ25620's ~QON}, it also gets the board\n  off Ship mode (if battery is present), or force a reset if pressed for 8.5 seconds."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 168.91 57.15 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1 1)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "ce89f747-ef7c-473e-a2ee-b354b59036c9")
	)
